<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-89 1403EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     12-23 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Guerrillas Attack Army Patrol, Kill 10 Soldiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas from the nation's
largest insurgent group ambushed an army patrol in southern
Colombia on Saturday, killing 10 soldiers, an army communique said.
   The attack came just hours after another leftist guerrilla
group, the April 19 Movement, announced it had suspended a
tentative peace pact after Congress failed to approved key parts of
the accord.
   Guerrillas belonging to the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia blew up part of the road south of the town of San Martin
as an army patrol traveling in three vehicles passed over it, the
communique said.
   The insurgents then opened fire on the patrol with automatic
weapons and rockets, killing 10 soldiers and injuring an
undetermined number, said the communique, read in a radio broadcast
by the Caracol network.
   The communique added that forces from the army's 7th Brigade
were still fighting the guerrillas who perpetrated the attack. San
Martin is 65 miles south of Bogota in Meta state.
   Founded about 30 years ago, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, with its estimated 5,000 armed rebels, is the oldest and
largest of Colombia's six main guerrilla groups.
   Another group, the April 19 Movment, said Saturday that it would
not lay down its weapons and accept a government amnesty this month
as originally planned.
   The movement cited as the reason for its decision Congress's
failure to approve key points of an official peace plan, which were
included in legislation to reform the country's constitution.
   The Senate shelved the legislation Dec. 14, after the House
attached a bill allowing a national vote on Colombia's extradition
of drug traffickers.
   The Senate apparently accepted President Virgilio Barco's
argument that the extradition referendum would lead to increased
terrorist violence by traffickers trying to pressure the public
into rejecting extradition.
   The shelving of the reform legislation was viewed as a victory
for the Barco administration's struggle against traffickers but a
blow to its efforts to make peace with the April 19 Movement and
other leftist groups.
   The legislation would have created a special electoral system
allowing the movement to elect members to Congress with fewer votes
than normally required. The group had demanded the concession in
return for its agreement to lay down its arms.
   A joint communique issued Saturday by the April 19 Movement's
leaders and government negotiators said the agreement has been
suspended but not discarded. ``Its contents are still valid, and
its negotiators have the responsibility to make it a reality,'' the
communique said.
   Both sides expressed ``the will to continue seeking dialogue and
negotiation.'' A new round of talks to save the pact is to begin in
January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891223-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-89 1405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     12-23 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighting Rages Between Shiite Militias in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias backed by
Syria and Iran fought daylong tank and artillery battles in south
Lebanon on Saturday, killing at least 17 people and wounding 45,
police said.
   Most of the casualties reported were from the Syrian-backed Amal
movement, but police could not give a specific breakdown. Amal's
rival, the pro-Iranian fundamentalist Hezbollah, or Party of God,
appeared to have the upper hand in the fighting that began north of
Sidon, 25 miles south of Beirut.
   At least six Shiite civilians, two of them children, were taken
to Beirut's American University Hospital with serious wounds, radio
stations reported.
   Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Cyprus, said
First Deputy Foreign Minister Ali Mohammad Besharati left for
Damascus ``to settle the differences'' between Hezbollah and Amal.
   Meetings between representatives of both sides were held in
Sidon ``in a bid to stop the fighting and prevent more bloodshed,''
official sources said.
   It was the latest eruption in a 2-year-old power struggle
between Amal and Hezbollah for control of Lebanon's 1.2 million
Shiites, the country's largest sect.
   Police were unsure what sparked the fighting, which torpedoed a
truce mediated by Syria and Iran that halted fighting between the
Shiite rivals last month.
   By police count, 588 people have been killed and 1,624 wounded
in Amal-Hezbollah battles that have raged intermittently since May
1987.
   An Amal official conceded that his movement's fighters had been
driven out of four villages in a surprise pre-dawn Hezbollah
assault.
   The official, who identified himself by his nom de guerre of Abu
Hassan Qobeissi, told The Associated Press at Amal's forward
command post outside the village of Kfar Hatta that the Hezbollah
forces attacked from their hill stronghold around the villages of
Jbaa and Ein Bouswar.
   The attackers overran four Amal-held villages, Kfar Hatta,
Mjaidel, Kfar Kila and Kfar Milki, he said.
   ``We were taken by surprise, but we're now counterattacking to
try to recapture the four villages,'' Qobeissi said as smoke from
burning buildings billowed into the sky.
   Police reported heavy fighting, with both sides using tanks,
mortars and rocket-propelled grenades around the contested villages.
   Hundreds of villagers fled toward Sidon, the provincial capital
of south Lebanon.
</TEXT>
